Results- Bayesian parameter optimization¶

Here, rather than performing a grid search, I will use Bayesian hyperparameter optimization. The idea behind a Bayesian approach to hyperparameter optimization is that we can model the performance of the algorithm as a Gaussian Process. In this case, we can think of this as regressing a the SNR (or other scoring function) on the hyperparameters of the model. Let us call the scoring function $f$.

This works by assuming that the joint distribution of $f(x_1), \ldots, f(x_n)$ has covariance $\Sigma$ of the form $\Sigma_{i,j} k(x_i, x_j)$ for some kernel function $k$, where $x_i$ are the hyperparameters to optimize (perhaps vectors of hyperparameters in the case of multiple parameters to tune). Then, after observing some number of points, the next point is determined by an Upper Confidence Bound, which has some balance between choosing points in locations that are thought to be optimal, and chooisng points that are distant from those already explored. I am evaluating this strategy to see how it compares to a random grid search over approximately the same range.

In [51]:
def snr(x):
    return 20 * (np.log10(1e-8 + x.mean()) -
                 np.log10(1e-8 + (x.reshape(-1) - im.reshape(-1)).std()))


def mse(x):
    return np.mean((x.reshape(-1) - im.reshape(-1))**2)


def tikh_target(A, b, logreg, fitness):
    recon = tikhonov(A, b, 10**(logreg))
    return fitness(recon), recon


def tv_target(A, b, logalpha, logreg, fitness):
    recon = split_bregman(A, b, 10**(logalpha), 10**(logreg), niter=75)
    return fitness(recon), recon


def gamma_target(A, b, logshape, logscale, fitness):
    recon = gamma_reconstruct(
        A, b, 0.05, 10**(logscale), 10**logshape + 2, niter=75)
    return fitness(recon), recon


def bo_search(name, fitness=snr):
    bos = {}
    botk = BayesianOptimization(
        lambda logreg: tikh_target(*d[name], logreg, fitness)[0], {
            'logreg': (-3, 3)
        })
    botv = BayesianOptimization(
        lambda logreg, logalpha: tv_target(*d[name], logalpha, logreg, fitness)[0], {
            'logreg': (-3, 0.5),
            'logalpha': (-2, 1)
        })
    bog = BayesianOptimization(
        lambda logshape, logscale: gamma_target(*d[name], logshape, logscale, fitness)[0],
        {
            'logshape': (-3, -1),
            'logscale': (-3, 0.5)
        })
    bos['tikh'] = botk
    bos['tv'] = botv
    bos['gamma'] = bog
    botk.maximize()
    botv.maximize()
    bog.maximize()
    return bos

pt = 1
for ds in ['full', 'sparse']:
    for x in ['tv', 'tikh', 'gamma']:
        plt.subplot(2, 3, pt)
        plt.imshow(opts[ds][x][1].reshape(*im.shape))
        plt.axis('off')
        plt.title('%s, %s, \nmse=%.5f, snr=%.5f' % (
            pretty_names[ds],
            pretty_algs[x],
            mse(opts[ds][x][1]),
            snr(opts[ds][x][1]),
        ))
        pt += 1

Discussion¶

Above is a slightly more refined search over parameters for the optimal prior values. Of course, this is just overfitting the data, because we can only specify our prior before we see the data, but it is interesting to see how a Bayesian optimiazation approach can get paraemters that result in a better error than a grid search, even with comparable compute time. The gamma prior achieves a noticibly less noisy image than the TV or Tikhonov regularization, and it runs faster than TV (and much slower than Tikhonov), so it seems like it is a decent choice

Below, we can also see the same results using MSE as our measure of fitness instead. In the sparse setting, using MSE and SNR as a fitness metric lead to approximately equivalent results, but when we use it on the full convolution with noise added, TV and Gamma found better parameter settings using MSE. This could be due to random chance in the running of the algorithm, but it could also have to do with the structure of the MSE as a function of parameters. Overall, this seems to reinforce that using a Gamma prior on the derivative works best in both cases. When we do not retain all information, TV works significantly worse than the other methods, but when we have full information, it seems to do slightly better.
